 Pix 与 Flix https://ritholtz.com/2023/08/pix-vs-flix/Barry Ritholtz Thu, 17 Aug 2023 14:00:53 +0000 Behavioral Finance/PsychologyPhilosophy https://ritholtz.com/?p=318296 <p>我经常看到一种特殊类型的分析，这种分析很容易误导投资者。通常，它从一个重要的单个数据点开始，但缺乏上下文。这是对市场复杂性的过度简单化，很容易导致错误的结论。最近，超额储蓄是一个完美的例子，说明了如何缺乏……</p><p><a class="button" href="https://ritholtz.com/2023/08/pix-vs-flix/">阅读更多<i class="icon ion-arrow-right-c"></i></a></p><p><a rel="nofollow" href="https://ritholtz.com/2023/08/pix-vs-flix/">Pix vs. Flix 的</a>帖子首先出现在<a rel="nofollow" href="https://ritholtz.com">The Big Picture</a>上。</p> ; <p> <a href="https://www.pexels.com/photo/people-sitting-on-a-movie-theater-7513412/" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><img decoding="async" loading="lazy" class="alignnone wp-image-318456" src="https://ritholtz.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/pexels-bence-szemerey-7513412.jpg" alt="" width="720" height="480" srcset="https://ritholtz.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/pexels-bence-szemerey-7513412.jpg 1800w, https://ritholtz.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/pexels-bence-szemerey-7513412-300x200.jpg 300w, https://ritholtz.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/pexels-bence-szemerey-7513412-1024x683.jpg 1024w, https://ritholtz.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/pexels-bence-szemerey-7513412-768x512.jpg 768w, https://ritholtz.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/pexels-bence-szemerey-7513412-250x167.jpg 250w, https://ritholtz.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/pexels-bence-szemerey-7513412-1536x1024.jpg 1536w" sizes="(max-width: 720px) 100vw, 720px" /></a></p><p></p><p>我经常看到一种特殊类型的分析，这种分析很容易误导投资者。通常，它从一个重要的单个数据点开始，但缺乏上下文。这是对市场复杂性的过度简单化，很容易导致错误的结论。</p><p>最近， <a href="https://www.tker.co/p/fed-researchers-excess-savings-depleted" target="_blank" rel="noopener">《超额储蓄》</a>是一个完美的例子，说明缺乏背景如何影响你的思维。</p><p><strong><br />不再过剩？流行病储蓄减少</strong><br /><a href="https://ritholtz.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/excessnomore.png" target="_blank" rel="noopener"><img decoding="async" loading="lazy" class="alignnone wp-image-318425" src="https://ritholtz.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/excessnomore.png" alt="" width="400" height="287" srcset="https://ritholtz.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/excessnomore.png 1276w, https://ritholtz.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/excessnomore-300x215.png 300w, https://ritholtz.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/excessnomore-1024x733.png 1024w, https://ritholtz.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/excessnomore-768x550.png 768w, https://ritholtz.com/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/excessnomore-250x179.png 250w" sizes="(max-width: 400px) 100vw, 400px" /></a><br />资料来源： <a href="https://www.frbsf.org/our-district/about/sf-fed-blog/excess-no-more-dwindling-pandemic-savings/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">旧金山联邦储备银行</a></p><p>所有关于过剩储蓄下降了多少的讨论——例如，看看<a href="https://www.frbsf.org/our-district/about/sf-fed-blog/excess-no-more-dwindling-pandemic-savings/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">这个</a>、 <a href="https://www.foxbusiness.com/economy/americans-burning-excess-savings-pandemic-sf-fed-study-says" target="_blank" rel="noopener">这个</a>、 <a href="https://www.bloomberg.com/news/articles/2023-08-16/americans-have-almost-depleted-excess-savings-sf-fed-study-says?in_source=embedded-checkout-banner" target="_blank" rel="noopener">这个</a>或<a href="https://www.reuters.com/markets/global-markets-excess-savings-analysis-pix-2023-07-31/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">这个</a>——都忽略了大部分美元的来源：大流行期间的政府转移支付。他们还忘记了人们被关在里面两年了。他们患有“小屋热”，毫不奇怪，所有被压抑的需求都随着消费的激增而出现，尤其是夏季休闲旅行。有点疯狂是可以预料的，但我们应该小心，不要从看似一次性的、封锁后的狂欢中推断出来。</p><p>这让我想起一个糟糕的<a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Syllogism" target="_blank" rel="noopener">三段论</a>：</p><blockquote><p>观察单个数据点；<br />对此达成广泛的结论；<br />用贸易或投资想法来表达这一点</p></blockquote><p>任何单个数据点的问题在于现实世界是复杂、混乱的，并且充满随机性和噪声。当任何新的经济数据发布时，你真的不知道有多少是噪音，多少是信号。</p><p>如果您了解如何正确构建数据，则可以避免此类错误。受此困扰的不仅仅是新手投资者，还有很多投资者。我经常在财经媒体上看到这样的说法。这不仅仅是新近效应（有关这种偏见的更多信息，请参阅此）；事实上，我们都需要学习如何在更大的图景和整个时期内将数据置于背景中。</p><p>经济数据尤其嘈杂，可能会被修改，并且基于“<a href="https://ritholtz.com/2020/05/what-models-dont-know/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">错误但有用</a>”的模型。更重要的是，大多数都是数据系列的一部分，随着时间的推移可以形成趋势。</p><p>围绕该趋势线总是存在很多波动：正常波动、回调和价格突然飙升都是价格系列的正常波动。我的同事<a href="https://www.cnbc.com/2019/04/04/what-is-the-stock-market-and-how-does-it-relate-to-the-economy.html">乔什·布朗（Josh Brown）</a>用一个在公园里遛狗的人来比喻——人的路径是趋势，但狗在皮带末端狂野地来回走动是价格系列。</p><p>我喜欢这个比喻，因为它迫使你远离某个时刻，放远视野，看到更广阔的背景。不要单独考虑任何特定的价格或数据点，而是尝试在较长的数据系列中设想该价格。它更多的是观看事件的视频，而不是查看单个静态图像。我喜欢称之为“Flix vs Pix”。</p><p>思考趋势可以避免反应过度。使用趋势线或移动平均线可以适用于任何类型的数据系列。 3 个月移动平均线消除了 NFP 报告中的大部分噪音； 6 个月趋势超越了从消费者支出到资本支出等各个方面的定期修订和更新。想要股票出现一半不错的卖出信号吗？忽略策略师的报告并尝试 NDX 或 SPX 的 10 个月移动平均线。</p><p>趋势线的优点是它弥补了模型固有的弱点。 The noise, revisions, updates, and even model changes all kinda sort themselves out <em>eventually</em> . They are imperfect depictions of reality, but if they are consistent, they can provide a useful framework for directional changes.</p><p> People with investment horizons of years or decades should avoid getting pulled into very short-term news. This includes the monthly employment situation report and quarterly GDP releases.</p><p> The long term is a series of short terms. Never confuse the two…</p><p></p><p> <em>Previously</em> :<br /> <a href="https://ritholtz.com/2020/05/what-models-dont-know/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">What Models Don&#39;t Know</a> (May 6, 2020)</p><p> <a href="https://ritholtz.com/2014/07/confessions-of-an-inflation-truther/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Confessions of an Inflation Truther</a> (July 21, 2014)</p><p> <a class="gtrackexternal" href="http://www.ritholtz.com/blog/2013/01/things-i-dont-care-about/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Things I Don&#39;t Care About</a> (January 15th, 2013)</p><p> <a href="https://ritholtz.com/2013/10/more-signal-less-noise/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">More Signal, Less Noise</a> (October 25, 2013)</p><p> <a class="gtrackexternal" href="http://www.ritholtz.com/blog/2012/11/information-sources/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">The Price of Paying Attention</a> (November 2012)</p><p> <a href="https://ritholtz.com/2008/05/is-inflation-really-understated-no/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Is Inflation Really Understated? (No!)</a> (May 08, 2008)</p><p> <a class="gtrackexternal" href="http://www.ritholtz.com/blog/2005/06/apprenticed-investor-lose-the-news/" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Lose the News</a> (June 2005)</p><p> <a href="https://ritholtz.com/2004/04/fun-with-hedonics-or-how-i-learned-to-stop-worrying-about-cpi-and-love-inflation/" target="_blank" rel="noopener">Fun with Hedonics or: “How I learned to stop worrying about CPI and love inflation.”</a> (April 21, 2004)</p><p></p><p></p><p> __________</p><p> 1. Since this rhymes, it has to be true! That&#39;s why I didn&#39;t use: “ <em>Still Images vs. Moving Pictures</em> ”</p><p></p><p> The post <a rel="nofollow" href="https://ritholtz.com/2023/08/pix-vs-flix/">Pix vs. Flix</a> appeared first on <a rel="nofollow" href="https://ritholtz.com">The Big Picture</a> .</p> ;
